Tidy Tuesday : Merging Datasets

In data science, a very common challenge that you will encounter is the problem of merging datasets. Two datasets can be merged when they share one or more columns in common. Let’s take a look at the Tidy Tuesday dataset from this week, and see what we need to do in order to create visualizations of the dataset.

library(tidyverse)

broadband <- readr::read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2021/2021-05-11/broadband.csv')

broadband %>%

It looks like we have variables BROADBAND AVAILABILITY PER FCC and BROADBAND USAGE that are associated with each county in the United States. This means that we will need map data at the county level. Let’s use the urbnmapr package. First, run

devtools::install_github("UrbanInstitute/urbnmapr")

We now have access to a dataset of county level data:

county <- urbnmapr::counties

Here is where our merging problem comes up- we need to add the BROADBAND AVAILABILITY PER FCC and BROADBAND USAGE variables to the county dataset. There are a few different ways that this merge can be made- full_join, left_join, right_join, and anti_join. The word infront of “join” refers to the dataset which keeps all of its values. full_join keeps all of the values from each dataset, filling in NA for values that don’t appear in the other dataset. left_join and right_join keep all values from the dataset on the left and right, respectively, and anti_join gives all of the values that weren’t matched in the merge. The syntax works as follows:

left_dataset %>%
  full_join(right_dataset, by = column_in_common)

If the columns of the datasets don’t have the same name, this is not a big deal. Use the syntax by = c("left_column_name" = "right_column_name"). In our case, it is natural to want to merge on the county names, which we do below. I am using a left_join because I want to preserve all of the values from the map data.

county %>%
  left_join(broadband, by = c("county_name" = "COUNTY NAME")) %>%
  head()
## # A tibble: 6 x 16
##    long   lat order hole  piece group   county_fips state_abbv state_fips

## 1 -86.9  32.7     1 FALSE 1     01001.1 01001       AL         01

Great! It looks like the two columns from the broadband dataset have been added. Before we keep going, I want to give you a pro tip- always check whether values have been excluded because of name mismatches. Did that happen here? Let’s use the anti_join function to check. I am using the select() function to restrict the output the county names and state abbreviations, and then the distinct() function to take out duplicates.

county %>%
  anti_join(broadband, by = c("county_name" = "COUNTY NAME")) %>%
  select(county_name, state_abbv) %>%
  distinct()
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   county_name          state_abbv
##   <chr>                <chr>     
## 1 La Salle Parish      LA        
## 2 Oglala Lakota County SD

We can see that there are two counties which have been excluded- La Salle Parish and Oglala Lakota County. This means that these counties do not occur in both datasets, or that there is a mismatch in the names of these counties across the datasets. Let’s look at what is happening:

We see that the La Salle Parish is named LaSalle Parish in the broadband dataset. We will need to fix these problems manually. We can use mutate() and gsub() to search through the county_name column and replace the names that we want to adjust. Recall that gsub() searches through a string, and replaces any matches with the second argument provided. Using the anti_join function, we can check that everything is fixed:

county %>%
  mutate(county_name = gsub("Oglala Lakota County","Oglala County", county_name),
         county_name = gsub("La Salle Parish","LaSalle Parish", county_name)
         ) %>%
  anti_join(broadband, by = c("county_name" = "COUNTY NAME")) %>%
  select(county_name, state_abbv) %>%
  distinct()
## # A tibble: 0 x 2
## # … with 2 variables: county_name <chr>, state_abbv <chr>

Great- it looks like we don’t have any values that have been dropped. Now, we are ready to use the data to create a choropleth map, like we looked at in a previous Tidy Tuesday document. Right now, BROADBAND AVAILABILITY PER FCC and BROADBAND USAGE are categorical variables- we should treat them as being numerical. Again, we can use the mutate() function to do this.

county %>%
  mutate(county_name = gsub("Oglala Lakota County","Oglala County", county_name),
         county_name = gsub("La Salle Parish","LaSalle Parish", county_name)
         ) %>%
  left_join(broadband, by = c("county_name" = "COUNTY NAME")) %>%
  mutate(`BROADBAND USAGE` = 100*as.numeric(na_if(`BROADBAND USAGE`, "-"))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(long,lat, group = group, fill = `BROADBAND USAGE`)) + 
  #This makes the borders of the counties transparent
  geom_polygon(color = NA) +
  #This controls the map projection and the bounds for the map
  coord_map(projection = "albers", lat0 = 39, lat1 = 45) +
  labs(x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude", fill = " ") +
  #theme_void makes it so no grid lines or tick marks are shown. We don't want these because we moved Alaska and Hawaii.
  theme_void() + 
  ggtitle("% of People per County with Access to Broadband Internet")

This map might benefit from binning the numerical variables.

county %>%
  mutate(county_name = gsub("Oglala Lakota County","Oglala County", county_name),
         county_name = gsub("La Salle Parish","LaSalle Parish", county_name)
         ) %>%
  left_join(broadband, by = c("county_name" = "COUNTY NAME")) %>%
  mutate(`BROADBAND USAGE` = 100*as.numeric(na_if(`BROADBAND USAGE`, "-")),
         `BROADBAND USAGE` = cut(`BROADBAND USAGE`, breaks = c(0,25,50,75,100))) %>%
  ggplot(aes(long,lat, group = group, fill = `BROADBAND USAGE`)) + 
  geom_polygon(color = NA) +
  coord_map(projection = "albers", lat0 = 39, lat1 = 45) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Pastel 2", na.value = "gray", labels = c("0-25%","25-50%","50-75%","75-100%")) +
  labs(x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude", fill = " ") +
  theme_void() + 
  ggtitle("% of People per County with Access to Broadband Internet")
